segments.text: I am with Mr. Roy Bliler, class of 1950.
My name is John Hatch.
I'm a member of Dr. Anderson's History 347 class.
Mr. Bliler, I think if we could start off with, I'm going to ask you some questions.
It should be able to pick you up.
Could you please state your name and your rank when you first entered the Army Air Corps?
Well, I went, to give you a little background, I was a National Guardsman.
And I went with the 200 and, hell, I can't remember the number of it now, but it was a post artillery antiaircraft in 1941 as a sergeant.
And then on January, on New Year's Eve day,
I got orders to report to the Air Force at Williams Air Force Base.
I had applied for transfer to the Air Force at that time.
So it was January 1st, 1941, and I was a buck sergeant.
What was your full name?
Roy Casson Lyler.
K-A-S-S-O-N. All right.
And what was your rank again?
You were a?
Sergeant, grade four.
Okay.
Okay.
And then what was your rank when you finally retired?
First lieutenant.
First lieutenant.
Okay.
Now, how old were you when you were first commissioned?
And how did you go, where did you go for your commissioning?
Well, I was commissioned in the Air Force as a bombardier.
And it was the 19th day of December, 1941.
I was commissioned.
Did I answer your question?
Yes.
All right.
Okay.
Again, how old were you at this time?
I was 22.
Okay, 22.
And now, in reference, how old were some of the men that you served with at the time?
Well, they ran from, I think the youngest was 19.
They were commissioning them at 18 in those days, but most of them who were second lieutenants were 19 to 25.
And how about some of the enlisted?
What were their age groups?
You know, I can't really honestly tell you.
They were young.
Probably 20 to 25.
Okay.
Now,
Do you, for all you know, are you the last Aggie survivor of the Aleutians?
I don't know.
I haven't had contact with any of them for years.
I don't know.
I just don't know.
I would hope that this could put me in touch with some of them.
Okay.
Now, you mentioned that you did not attend Texas A&M at first.
You came back after the war.
No.
Okay.
Could you explain that just a little bit?
Well, I went to a little old teacher's college in Minnesota in 1940, 41, 39, 40.
And I was, it was, there was nothing to study for but to be a teacher, and I wanted to be an engineer, but that was hopeless at the time because I couldn't afford it.
I lived at home and went to school.
What was the question again?
I came to the U.N. right after the war in 1945, and enrolled as a chemical engineer.
And some of those credits counted.
I got about a year's credit.
I had two years of college.
I got about a year's credit out of that teacher's college for my degree.
Okay.
Now, would you state, basically in your own words, what the United States military's purpose was in the Aleutian Island campaign?
Well, it was to drive the Japanese out of the Aleutian Islands.
You see, the Aleutian Islands were owned by the United States.
They were purchased in the original Seward purchase years ago.
And the Japanese invaded the Aleutian Islands, and they invaded two islands.
And our objective was to get them the hell out of there before they came on down the west coast.
They were a little afraid that they would come down the west coast.
It turned out later they had no intention of it.
It was diversionary, but we didn't know that at the time.
I guess that answers your question.
We wanted to get them the hell out of there.
All right.
Could you kind of explain where the Aleutian Islands are located?
You mentioned it's on the west coast.
Well, it's off the west coast of Alaska.
Matt?
Be prepared, my buddy.
This is Alaska.
Here we are.
All right.
Now they start here and then they come on.
They string on out.
Yes, sir.
Into the Bering Sea.
Okay.
And that's colder than hell up there.
The water's cold, even in the summertime.
But these are the islands, and I was on Jetson-Kiscon Attitudes up here.
And I ended up on this island right here.
If she was out, okay.
Ms. Andrea Hollins was a part of the chain, the illusion chain.
Jessica and Chick Holland, that right there, that's the one I ended up on.
I made a few raids out of Adak Holland, but that was too far back.
So we moved up to Farming.
They put up
landing strip on Amchitka Island.
And we loaded onto there.
And we went there.
They told us, it's in the book, by the way, they told us that we would be just an overnight stay.
We went from this island here to go out and raid Kiska.
And we would have come back and land and spend the night there.
There was no runway there.
They told us it would be just overnight, and we spent three months there.
Okay.
They lied to us.
They didn't want to get us in trouble.
They, you mean the brass?
Yeah.
I was in the B-25, which was a twin-engine bomber.
It was called, nicknamed the Billy Mitchell, because Billy Mitchell was a famous general in the World Air Force before the war.
He died before the war, I think.
But he had a big hand in the development of the B-25.
Wonderful airplane.
Brought me back many times.
Can you kind of go into more detail about your mission and your responsibility?
You said you were a bombardier.
Bombardier.
I dropped bombs from up there.
Hell from heaven boys, they called us.
And we never hit anything, it seemed like.
We used to come down and the colonel would get us together and he'd cheer out the bombardier because he was partial to the pilots.
And one of the bombardiers told him, he said, well, colonel, how can we hit anything if we don't have a stable platform?
He says, the pilots keep moving on.
He says, that's your problem.
In reading the article, one thing that interested me was the, you mentioned something about not all the planes hit the site, the bombardier site.
Yeah.
Could you kind of explain the site?

Well, usually they'd have a lead plane go up, and he'd drop bombs, and he'd drop them just a little bit short of the turret so that the planes that were with him, you know, in formation, their bombs would go off and hit the turret.
Once in a while, we hit it lucky.
We just had too much unstable weather and too many unstable pilots.
Of course, if I'd have been a pilot, I'd have probably been unstable, too.
How often did you go on combat missions?
I think I'm listed 23 missions.
23 of them, I think.
Now, that's official missions.

Now, those that we avoided, you know, you'd get up and then you'd run into some weather and you couldn't get there and you'd wander around and hope to hell you'd find the island again, come back and land.
That wasn't a mission because you didn't drop your bombs.
Okay.
So how did that work out for a week, basically?
23 missions in six months.
So, in other words, you didn't see active combat every day, I guess?
Oh, no.
No.
A lot of active weather, but not a lot of active combat.
Speaking of weather, I noticed in your article you mentioned something about some very powerful windstorms.
What are they called?
Could you explain that a little bit?
Well, it was a freak wind that happened all the time up there.
But it would come up, we'd get up in the morning and we'd have a still ocean.
It was just perfectly calm.
And all of a sudden the clouds would just come from nowhere.
And then the wind would start to blow.
And the worldwide wind would get up as much as 300 miles an hour.
And it blew a lot of the boys out to sea and they never recovered because the planes would only go 200 miles an hour.
If they turned into this wind and tried to get back, they flew backwards.
Now, I didn't put that in there.
I sure didn't, I guess.
That's one of the things I didn't mention.
Well, how did they keep everything tied down in those kind of winds?
Well, they had what they called revetments.
They'd come in with a bulldozer, and that shell was kind of peculiar.
They'd have some gravel sometimes, and they'd find that, and they'd build revetments.
which would be a good open space with a wall.
And they'd put the planes in there, taxi them in there, and we walk them in, and then tie them down.
And then if the wind hit, it would flop them around, but it wouldn't blow them away because they were tied down.
Okay.
Now how about, okay.
It's back to your combinations.
Were you ever wounded in any of the times that you were?
One time, and I mentioned it in there, I don't know whether they called it a wound or not.
The flight surgeon didn't call it a wound.
The windshield, something hit the windshield and shattered it, and a piece of glass, I think, hit my finger.
I still got my scar from it.
It wasn't much of a wound, but it, well, here it is.
But it bled like a stud hog.
It just bled all over the place.
But I went back to him.
We landed, and I went to the flight surgeon.
He put some alcohol on it, and he said, hell, you're not hurt, boy.
There's blood all over you.
Well, where'd all that blood come from?
He said, well, I don't know, but you're not hurt.
Back to duty.
I said, well, don't I at least get a purple heart?
No.
I don't know what hit me.
I think a piece of plexiglass.
A shell went through the windshield, a piece of plexiglass.
I know in the story you explained it.
Explain where your place in the plane is, I think.
No, right up front, no.
Underneath.
Well, it's kind of, yeah, I guess you went underneath to get there, but it was up front.
You could look back and see the pilot.
Okay.
You could look down and see you.
But, yeah, it was in the nose.
And incidentally, I mentioned in there, we had to land and take off in the nose in the most dangerous place of the airplane.
Because if you crashed, whatever she would, we had to because the pilot, depending on the bombardier for his eyes, you couldn't see much below you because of the fog.
The bombardier could see a little bit.
And I explained in there how
We'd come to an island.
They'd pick out an island with a radar to find it, and then they'd fly along the coast until a bombardier spotted some barrels.
The Air Force had put out floating barrels, anchor barrels.
And then the bombardier would call upon John, we're here, and so he'd make a 270-degree turn and come in over those barrels.
Well, the runway was 50 feet above the ocean.
So he had to raise it 50 feet.
And then you couldn't see the runway until you got right on it.
And the bomber would tell him whether he was on the runway or not, knew it.
And then he would drop down, and then the pilot couldn't see the runway.
It was scary as hell.
How often did you receive R&R?
I never got it.
I was offered it one time, and I turned it down.
And don't ask me why.
I think, looking back, I think I was afraid that if I went for a while or not, I'd be afraid to come back.
I think that was the thinking.
But, well, all of them, I guess, except me, went back.
They called me a dumbass.
But some of them went back, and they cracked up.
They couldn't take it.
What did you do to occupy your time when you weren't flying?
Played a lot of poker in the bridge.
Drank a lot of torpedo juice when we could get it.
Which is?
Well, torpedo juice is, I mentioned it in there, it's medical alcohol.
The flight surgeon had strict control of it.
He would give the pilot a Coke bottle full of it.
Ron?
Yeah?
Excuse me, we're at my dad's while we're here.
Do you want to come in and meet Mr. Hatch?
What do you want?
We were talking about your honor, what you did, Dr., by your time, whenever.
Well, drank a lot of that.
Well, we'd take the flight surgeon and we'd give a Coke bottle full to the pilot.
There were seven men on the crew.
Six or seven.
Ten.
And the pilot would take it back to the Quonset head, or the tent, if we were in tents.
And he would cut it in half with water.
And then he'd take that, he'd mix that, and then he'd cut that in half with grapefruit juice.
We had plenty of grapefruit juice for some reason.
Not much else, but grapefruit juice.
And then he was divided up in the canteen cups among all the crew members.
We each got mugged about a swallow, which he'd get drunk or held.
Well, how well were the troops supplied as far as equipment?
Well, another anecdote.
He had a buddy who got shot down.
Fortunately, he was rescued.
But somehow or another, for some reason, he wore my hard hat, my helmet, out there.
And he lost it in the drink.
He came back and I said, where's my helmet?
He says, hell, I lost it in the drink.
So I went to the supply officer.
I said, hey, I need a helmet.
He says, god damn.
He says, why didn't you lose an airplane helmet?
We can supply an airplane like that, but we can't help it.
Okay.
So the supply wasn't too good.
You mentioned we were like a living condition on the different islands.
I know you mentioned you had different conditions.
Well, Amchitka wasn't so good until toward the last.
Amchitka was a burning outpost.
And the warlock came and blew our tents away, blew everything away.
like to drown us.
And that's when somebody got wind of it and sent in some people from the attitude in general.
So plenty of them.
Can you imagine that?
And they came in and landed after that one o'clock and looked into our condition.
And they said, hell, this is terrible.
He says, you're going to go back for, they didn't call it R&R.
They called it, I don't know,
rest, I guess.
You're going to go back and get some rest.
If we could rest before you come back.
So, all the guys there wanted to go, except me.
And I said, no, I don't think I'll go.
I think I'll stay here and just straighten out.
They brought some onset heads, and I had to help set it up.
I didn't have to, but I did.
Because I was afraid.
I never did tell anybody this.
So I have to do this, do this.
I was brutally terrified that I would not come back.
I was afraid they'd get me for desertion.
Because I was just, I was exhausted by that time.
I'd had too much combat.
In fact, the adjutant told me finally, he says, you've had too damn much combat.
He says, you realize you've been here longer than anybody?
I said, no way.
Okay.
Well, how long were you there from when you originally were stationed until they finally sent you home?
Let me see.
Turn that off for a minute.
I want to send that.
Now, that was as interesting as it was there.
Where was my permission?
That's what I mentioned.
I fell over dead in the air.
Sixty-four of the men who had been in class number 4217, on December 20, 1942.
That's when I got my commission.
What was the question?
How long did you serve from when you first were stationed in the Aleutians to when you finally went home?
Let's see.
We departed from there, from Seattle, on 26th of February, 43, via C-47 headed north.
So that's when I first went to Volusia Island.
26th of February, 43.
I came home.
17th of September, 1943.
We're not here the first day.
February.
February.
March, April, May, June, July, August, September, seven months.
And about six of those were in the islands.
Okay.
Was that an unusually long tour, or was that a...
a fairly rather normal turnover rate?
Well, nobody lasted much more than six months.
A lot of guys went crazy.
So that was an average tour, I would say, six months, seven months.
Okay.
A lot of guys, I got an ear infection out there.
I don't know what it was.
They called it the Emotion Crud.
And they put me in a hospital in Wichita Falls, an Air Force hospital.
And for some reason, they put me in psychiatric.
No, no, no.
And I got into this snake pit with a bunch of guys.
And I asked them, well, that chicken, emotions, they're all lost to mine.
So I went and told the surgeon.
He said, no, you're not.
He said, we'll get you out of there.
I spent a day with him.
But they had me under psychiatric treatment because they didn't know what this outbreak was in my ears.
They thought it might be psychiatric.
Turned out it wasn't.
They called it dilution of crud.
Pure, simple cure, just plain alcohol will chase it away.
But it
It's not permanent.
I have to treat them every now and still.
It was a bonus.
So they flew you back from the Aleutians to Wichita Falls to treat them?
No, they flew me back to Seattle.
Oh, and this was at the end of your tour?
Yes, at the end of my tour.
No, it was a couple years later that I went to Wichita Falls.
Oh, okay.
Let me see.
I don't know what I mean.
You know, Colonel Roosevelt was on that plane with me.
Yes.
And I asked him, I said, Colonel, I said, did he think that he or I would get bumped in case anyone got on with their priority?
And he said, maybe we'll find out.
In El Paso, Texas, we found out, but I didn't mind really.
I was on my way home, and this time my parachute was packed safely into the bus luggage.
I didn't mind at all.
Now, what happened was, you know, my parachute, God, that was my life.
It took it everywhere with me.
And so whenever we went on transport, I put it through on the transport.
I had it ready to wear.

But when we got to Seattle and got on the civilian plane, American Airways, I was carrying my parachute on board and the steward, they didn't have stewards, the steward says, I'll hire a lieutenant, you don't take that with you.
And I said, what's he mean by that?
He says, there's no opportunity to use it here.
He says, look at all these civilians.
He says, they don't have parachutes.
So I had to...
But there was luggage and that scared the hell out of me.
I didn't have my parachutes.
So I felt good about it when I finally got on that bus and it was back to where I was.
Okay.
How effective was the information coordination between the branches of the military?
Oh, it was terrible.
Terrible.
Of course, a lot of it we didn't see.
But the colonel used to say, I wish to God you guys would quit bitching about the Navy.
He says, after all, they are our allies.
No, that coordination was not good at all.
We'd go out on a raid.
Of course, the first thing that went out was the radio.
Every time we'd go on a raid, the radio would get so full of static.
I guess it was jam, I don't know, 20 or so or less static.
But you couldn't hear much.
We just took the headset off.
No, the coordination was not good at all.
I remember one time they were experimenting with radar up there.
They were going to make a raid on Kisk Island, which had a volcano on the west end of it.
And they were going to go up through the soil, and with radar, they were going to spot the target, the Navy had it on their plane, and they were going to bomb it.
And we would be on the Navy's wing, and when they released their bombs, we would release ours.
Well, God damn, the Navy flew us right into the volcano.
And the lead ship crashed, blam, into the volcano.
We would have been over it.
So...
The colonel says, what the hell were those birds?
Could you explain the fish hook ridge?
Well, it was just a mountainous group that was shaped like a fish hook in the air, just like a fish hook.
And a lot of fighting went on there between our ground troops and the Japanese ground troops.
And we were told that the Japs had taken Fish Hook Ridge.
We were told to bomb them out of there.
So we went and bombed it, and meanwhile our troops took it.
But they didn't get their panels out.
No day.
So we just blew them to hell, our own boys.
And the leader, the leader was honky-tonking Anchorage on my way home.
A GI came up to me and he says, Lieutenant, he says, how many damn machine guns do you have on those B-25s?
I said, well, some of them had five or six and some of them got two.
